{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586138"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:26:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:26:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15065"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15065"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67764"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7753"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15065"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53229"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7684"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18930"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67764"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMinimal change disease is the most common cause of nephrotic syndrome in children. On light microscopy, the glomeruli appear normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the characteristic ultrastructural finding in minimal change disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Podocyte foot process effacement","Immune complex deposits in the basement membrane","Thickening of the glomerular basement membrane","Mesangial cell proliferation","Subepithelial spike formation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hallmark finding in minimal change disease is \u003Cstrong\u003Epodocyte foot process effacement\u003C/strong\u003E visible only on electron microscopy. Light microscopy appears completely normal, which gives the condition its name.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmune complex deposits in the basement membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - These are characteristically absent in minimal change disease, unlike other causes of nephrotic syndrome such as membranous nephropathy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThickening of the glomerular basement membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - The basement membrane remains normal in minimal change disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesangial cell proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E - There is no proliferation of any glomerular cells in minimal change disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubepithelial spike formation\u003C/strong\u003E - These \u0027spikes\u0027 are characteristic of membranous nephropathy, not minimal change disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe podocyte foot process effacement leads to disruption of the glomerular filtration barrier, resulting in selective proteinuria and nephrotic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Minimal change disease is characterised by podocyte foot process effacement visible on electron microscopy","Minimal change disease is the most common cause of nephrotic syndrome in children","Light microscopy appears normal in minimal change disease, with changes only visible on electron microscopy"],"references":["Saha TC, Singh H. Minimal change disease: a review. South Med J. 2006 Nov;99(11):1264-70. doi: 10.1097/01.smj.0000243183.87381.c2. PMID: 17195422.","Vivarelli M, Massella L, Ruggiero B, Emma F. Minimal Change Disease. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2017 Feb 7;12(2):332-345. doi: 10.2215/CJN.05000516. Epub 2016 Dec 9. PMID: 27940460; PMCID: PMC5293332.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53229"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15065"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53229"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T22:21:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T22:22:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7753"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67764"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving informat